Comment: To be fair, you have to have a very high IQ to understand Morbius. The conflict and character development is extremely subtle, and without a solid grasp of classic English dramatic literature, most of the weight of the scenario will go over a typical viewer's head. There's also Michael's nihilistic outlook, which is deftly woven into his characterisation- his personal philosophy draws heavily from Narodnaya Volya literature, for instance. The fans understand this stuff; they have the intellectual capacity to truly appreciate the depths of these scenes, to realise that they're not only humorous- they say something deep about LIFE. As a consequence, people who dislike Morbius truly ARE idiots- of course they wouldn't appreciate, for instance, the depth in Morbius' quote: "I am Venom. <snarls> Just kidding, I'm Dr. Michael Morbius at your service." which itself is a cryptic reference to Turgenev's Russian epic Fathers and Sons. I'm smirking right now just imagining one of those addlepated simpletons scratching their heads in confusion as Jared Leto's genius wit unfolds itself exclusively on the cinematic screens this April 1st. What fools.... how I pity them.

Comment:
I think there's a really good explanation of what's going on in the next few marvel movies.

So by the looks of it from this trailer the different Spider Man universe have all merged into one that resides in the MCU. However, people are remembering things incorrectly.

If you think back to the first trailer where this whole thing starts. Because of Doctor Strange's remembering spell perhaps requiring parts of the multiverse to be trapped into and it being disrupted, it all makes sense why all these elements of the different universes are now popping up. 

This is why Toby's Spider Man is behind the words "murder", but Instead of people remembering it as Tom's Spider Man "murdering" Mysterio, they remember it as Toby's doing. Its also why Oscorp exist in the MCU (presumably after NWH), why Morbis knows of Venom, why doc ock recognize Tom as his Spider Man.

All these things that have happened before still occurred, but just everyone remembers this differently. This whole remembering element combined with the multiverse aspects you can start to connect more of the pieces together. Does this mean Toby and Andrew shows in the movie(s)? We still can't know for sure without another trailer, or just seeing the movie, but it does for sure give us more supporting evidence that many of us will be happy with NWH and Morbus when they release.

Plenty of MCU solo installments are widely regarded as nothing above filler content, which I wouldn‚Äôt say makes for great world building. 20+ films in the span of a decade is a LOT of ‚Äúgroundwork‚Äù for a single franchise. Comment: Apparently, SONY has made changes in Michael's superpowers. Morbius is a lab-created pseudo-vampire who does not have the weaknesses of traditional vampires. Now Michael has echolocation - the ability to pick up objects using sonar. This ability allows bats not only to navigate in the air, but also helps them find their prey by the sound of his breathing. Michael doesn't have wings, but he has the ability to fly by pushing off the air. Since many bats communicate with each other through low-frequency sounds, Morbius can summon a swarm of bats. And it seems that Michael's vampirism is divided into 2 states: in one, he is in a human shell, retaining the abilities of bats, but in a state of bloodlust, he turns into a creepy monster, acquiring fangs and claws.

Comment: Inarguably the best film I've ever seen. Once you watch it once you will have to watch it over and over because it's so complex and mindbending that you just won't get it the first couple times around. The godfather is okay. Apocalypse Now is great. Titanic left me on the edge of my seat even though I knew what was about to happen... But morbius... Makes Shawshank feel like a nickelodeon movie directed by Dan Schneider. Brilliant, absolutely brilliant but it won't truly be appreciated for another 20 years. People just don't get the complexity or the drama but once the credits roll they will be looking at their fingers just to realize they bit down to the nail bed. Hope they make so many sequels but I highly doubt they will be as good as this masterpiece. The tone, the setting, omg the acting, the premise, and the determination from the director is unrivaled. I don't just love this movie.. We have a relationship

Comment:
Low and behold, it‚Äôs officially 1 year old!!!

Very upsetting again they cut so much footage from those trailers 
I'm actually not hating this by any means even if it's too short 
Jared Leto is good, you feel his calculated passion combating his ailment and the movie moves by so fast 
Is he here to heal the world or to destroy it? 
I like Matt Smith as his best friend/rival, he's having fun with the material especially towards the climax 
This is Marvel exploring more of the supernatural/horror side of things than most superhero movies 
The effects for when Morbius flies look like slick oil paintings pulsating from his body meant to give a sense of ripple effects 
True they're not perfect but still work given how he has to move in this environment 
Tyrese Gibson's detective could be cut out of this entirely as well as Jared Harris 
Not too many Spider-Man references, maybe 1 or 2
The mid credits scene ties to Spider-Man: Homecoming and No Way Home thankfully 
The after credits scene is really good too! 
I'm still banking on that Sinister Six movie if it does ever get made 
Science is about taking risks and testing the boundaries otherwise it's meaningless, should healthy people know what death is like when sick people have had to live with it longer, how long before the remedy is worse than the disease, how far are we to fix something that's broken?, science and evolution are either different or the same in many regards, our bodies are like a puzzle it's just that the pieces are missing 
SONY and Marvel and director Daniel Espinoza have made a fairly watchable entry in their canon if not their finest; still has its share of good acting from Leto and Smith even if the romance with Arjona is very weak and the film doesn't intentionally scare you 
There's still possible potential for future side stories 
Let's just hope the studios can land their footing

Comment:
Once upon a time, in a world where superheroes and villains roamed freely, there was a strange and enigmatic character named Morbius. He was known as the Living Vampire, with the power to control the life force of those around him. Despite his fearsome reputation, Morbius was not always the fearsome figure he appeared to be. In fact, he was often quite comical and prone to making jokes, much to the annoyance of his enemies.

One day, Morbius was feeling particularly mischievous. He had heard that there was going to be a gathering of heroes and villains in the city square, and he couldn't resist the opportunity to have some fun. As he stood atop a nearby building, he gazed down at the crowd below, a wicked grin spreading across his face. He raised his arms into the air and declared in his best dramatic voice, "It's Morbin' time!"

With that, Morbius let loose his powers, engulfing the entire square in a swirling mass of energy. Those below, whether hero or villain, were sent flying in every direction, unable to resist the force of Morbius' attack. The ground rumbled and the buildings shook, as Morbius continued to release his energy, wreaking havoc upon the city.

The heroes and villains quickly regained their footing and began to rally against Morbius, but he was too powerful for them to overcome. He continued to dance and twirl, laughing and cackling as he made his way through the city, leaving destruction in his wake. Everywhere he went, people ran in terror, unable to comprehend the sheer power of the Living Vampire.

It wasn't until later that day, when Morbius finally tired himself out and returned to his lair, that he realized what he had done. The city was in ruins, and many people had been injured in his outburst. But even as he looked upon the destruction he had caused, Morbius couldn't help but laugh. After all, it was Morbin' time.

Comment: Inarguably the best film I've ever seen. Once you watch it once you will have to watch it over and over because it's so complex and mindbending that you just won't get it the first couple times around. The godfather is okay. Apocalypse Now is great. Titanic left me on the edge of my seat even though I knew what was about to happen... But morbius... Makes Shawshank feel like a nickelodeon movie directed by Dan Schneider. Brilliant, absolutely brilliant but it won't truly be appreciated for another 20 years. People just don't get the complexity or the drama but once the credits roll they will be looking at their fingers just to realize they bit down to the nail bed. Hope they make so many sequels but I highly doubt they will be as good as this masterpiece. The tone, the setting, omg the acting, the premise, and the determination from the director is unrivaled. I don't just love this movie.. We have a relationship
